  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and expectations for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries agree to cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n- Allows for information sharing and joint legal actions\n- Enables cross-border evidence gathering and asset seizure\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Countries align their legal definitions and regulatory frameworks\n- Standardizes approaches to detecting and preventing money laundering\n- Creates more consistent enforcement mechanisms\n\n4. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow international standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) and Customer Due Diligence (CDD) protocols\n- Reporting suspicious transactions across jurisdictions\n\n5. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International bodies can impose sanctions on non-compliant countries\n- Financial institutions face potential penalties for inadequate anti-money laundering controls\n- Encourages consistent implementation of anti-money laundering strategies\n\nThese intersections create a complex but increasingly coordinated global approach to combating financial crimes.",
